'''''Super Trolley''''', is a [[1988 in video gaming|1988]] [[video game]] produced by Icon Design where the player takes control of a [[supermarket]] employee. It was created as a tie-in with the BBC show [[Jim'll Fix It]].

==Gameplay==
Players control a supermarket worker who is tasked with stocking the supermarket shelves, finding lost babies and removing dogs from the store. The objective of the game is to successfully complete each day's tasks from Monday through to Saturday, the latter being the busiest day of the week, without being sacked. As this is accomplished the player's character is promoted, eventually becoming the store manager and sacking his former employer.<ref name="crash">{{cite journal | last = Hamza| first = Katharina |author2=Roberts, Nick | title = Reviews - Super Trolley| journal = [[Crash (magazine)|Crash]]| issue =  52 | pages = 14| publisher = [[Newsfield]]| date = May 1988 }}</ref>

Before shelves can be filled the player must price each item in the warehouse,<ref name="zzap">{{cite journal | last = Houghton| first = Gordon |author2=Sumner, Paul | title = Budget Test - Super Trolley| journal = [[Zzap!64]]| issue =  40 | pages = 88| publisher = [[Newsfield]]| date = August 1988 }}</ref> which involves attaching labels to goods.<ref name="cvg">{{cite journal | last = Jenkins| first = Chris | title = Reviews - Super Trolley| journal = [[Computer and Video Games]]| issue =  80 | pages = 46| publisher = [[Dennis Publishing]]| date = June 1988 }}</ref>

==Development==
The game was developed after a wish by Andrew Collett was sent to the BBC's television programme, ''[[Jim'll Fix It]]''.<ref name="cvg"/> The inlay card artwork depicts a cartoon of the show's presenter [[Jimmy Savile]] pushing a shopping trolley.

